Notwithstanding these technical achievements and impressive applications, LLMs still have a variety of fundamental shortcomings.
 Figure (ref) illustrates some of these, by showing the responses of three different state-of-the-art models to a user question about Turing laureates born in Latin America.
 LLM1 lists two winners, but the first never won the Turing award.
 LLM2 lists two people who are indeed both Turing laureates, but the first one is born in Italy, not Latin America.
 Finally, the last LLM gives an empty list with the proviso that it was trained a while ago. 
 The ground-truth is that only Manuel Blum should be in a correct reply.